A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
In spite of this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have mentioned on Mobil.cz many times the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTU (Czech Telecommunications Office), which noted that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - the SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of cheaper Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Czech Telecommunications Office Council (CTU), who said on several occasions that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, complained to the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network seems to have no more chance (at present he would find only difficult frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable decrease in prices, to which the traditional operators must then also react.
However, even before the entry of the trouble-fests such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today at our home were heard in Great Britain.
However, it appeared that there was room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator of the country.
Let us add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:Fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile, relatively high network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators are profiled as low-cost operators - they offer calls and cheap SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile, in Great Britain, offers at least two times less expensive SMS than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, poorly targeting an unusual target group can also be a good start for advertising.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator that they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be possible to go to us too.
Miroslav Čepíký, Vodafone's spokesman, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
As far as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, the mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but negotiations in the Czech Republic are not very provocative.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their best so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business client field, has not been hiding for quite a long time his intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have a lot to do to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile services.
And the sooner it'll be the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl group.
So the future may be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At this point, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific ones.
For the time being, no matter provided with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeně of the Press Department of Phoneika O2, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not recorded for the moment a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time frame, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone rather directs its attention to the fulfilment of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepíký says in this regard: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think means most of the inputs from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a lower price and thus to a lower profit.
So what good is it to make it easier for such a competitor to happen?
When it comes to their interests, operators can understand themselves as larynx. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U.S. background also bears witness to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the ČTU, during the creation of the U:Fon, was that exercised by the T-Mobile company.
Evidence of information available to the public from the CTU website.
Now, today, the U:Fon is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "Competition in the mobile market has also been recently amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player will submit it, and especially its services, to high requirements."
However, given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies appears to be disappointing.
However, it is not only the attitude of the CTU, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator on the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the time being, because the offer of potential stakeholders did not prioritise enough interest for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the UOHS said in response to our question.
A statement thus made would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a statement is more than a waste.
Moreover, Kristian Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their market entry has contributed to a decrease in mobile phone service prices."
However, pressure in the sense of fair functioning of the market and a decrease in prices is apparently not part of the interests of the UOHS.
What is really shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, is of course a matter.
Similarly, a price of strictly identical essence to all service stations is probably due to the accident and the hard fight against competition.
"The Office has not, in this regard, recorded signs of anticompetitive behaviour, therefore there is no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, none of them therefore have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even missing from the telecommunication regulator," Chaloupa stated in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the CTU, according to which telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts suggest another vision of things: in order for a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the OAU that three mobile operators are manifestly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Reducing responsibility for ČTU is a fairly common turn in communications, whereby ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, there has been no success in the renewal of the Telecommunications Act, which has recently been adopted, an extension of CTU's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This is something that the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
This says, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies publishing their own price list of mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, there is a question of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, specific mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms are generally only available to the electorate.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company is made before the operator is a classic company client, which orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it receives special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a return.
"If what you are saying happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could result in a ceasefire with the company in question," answered our question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that an echo of such an activity will not reach the leaders of the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator shall object to such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these firms bring them indiscriminate benefits, and, at the same time, by contrast to the true virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot have it fully available in the way of regular clients of mobile operators."
However, this is precisely what should appear strange in the CTU.
In addition, there is another question in the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the UOHS has relatively large powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the operator's explanations, which claim that there is no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has significantly reduced the price of services.
However, in almost all countries where virtual operators appeared, classical operators were increasingly, more or less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that, in the developed countries, the regulatory bodies, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their clients, have intervened.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the form of a hot potato that is released by transmitting it to a close target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is more than beneficial in these cases.
But don't throw the stain after the cognac.
If the information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS can hardly remain unresolved in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech Hymne has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech National Hymne.
On Sunday, on the day of the Czech nationality, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the National Hymne Kde homev můj (Where is my homeland?).
Hymne was re-registered by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with heart and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Katerín Knězynková et Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the hymne arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted the Czech Republic's rzhlas (Czech public radio), he chose to interpret the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers, as well as the heart, had a good word, so that we could understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech National Hymne will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde mův můj held for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the theatre of the states) in Fidlovčka (Kermesse des saviers), the original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national hymne.
It will remain one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
