The Sudets were demanding a referendum in the United States
The Germans of the Sudettes demanded that Šumava be incorporated into the United States in 1945.
This comes from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vedecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the US patronage.
In 1945, certain groups of Germans from the South addressed the president of the United States with such a wish.
This comes from, among other things, a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vedecká knihovna.
From the Germans of Český Krumlov in the letter, the US president is asking not to allow the "shumavská zupa" (a region of forests south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have well understood the situation and we really want to be sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come into the territory not in oppressors and enemies, but in liberators," is written in the letter "People to whom the fortune of the Shumava is at heart."
Since the relationship to Czechoslovakia is not allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - that of brutality, indifference, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protection of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would give this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and destroys minorities and that nothing has contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the four million inhabitants," the letter says.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire to avenge the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States had doubts about the opinion of the Germans in Shumava, he would only have to organize a referendum in the region, according to the authors, to establish whether his people wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter can, in view of the current knowledge of the history of post-war, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudettes of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least consider that the issue of their expulsion from the republic was going to take place, very few of them had the opportunity to do so.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to obtain some form of autonomy for the South.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirmed it.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the marine in the Baltic countries.
At the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the catch camp in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them the Czech language.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," says Chalupa.
None of the Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, he believed that he would be expelled from the republic, following the Beneš Decrees.
