Hema-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of blood contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to highlight the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before she proudly stated that in early 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, maintains that "trust is something extremely fragile."
On 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe, which has been holding the strong since its founding in 1998.
"And we did not know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, which, when not known and which a serious disease can result from, in the case of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by a degenerence of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of those who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
Now, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: nuclear acid (TAN) tests that directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the donor blood and not of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed for the short period of mobility, which ranges between the time the person was infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our technicians, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, a person of 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before HIV is transmitted by a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel at ease with receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says Hema-Québec's head of management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
Hema-Quebec must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to security supplies, Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies.
"The needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need recharge in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors, which has an average of only 3% of Quebec's blood donation eligible."
However, every healthy person, aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have been travelling in a country where malaria occurs, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poverty is very rare.
But there is a need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and cannot give any more of their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so infrequent, it's rarely the time to spend an hour giving his blood," says Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec which also manages the only public blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was already considered a biomedical waste is a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the establishment of our thousand blood sample of cordon and is expected to take more than a thousand per year.
We should begin to propose this for graffiti at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this program of blood collection as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they can't have access there," because Hema-Québec has no means to propose this complex and expensive program in all Québec hospitals.
