Following an Orwellinian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has attempted to continue a six-million-dollar campaign against three authors and a small publishing house without the sound in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of prosecutions for defamation, but the law.
No surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone or to support a position contrary to his own?
No matter the outcome of the trial, the authors and editor of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defenses and fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the pockets almost without the bottom of the mine.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a regulation on the friend who will baililn the opposition in addition to defraying anyone who will dare to rethink the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in the public opinion that she should have presented her vision of facts.
Contrary to what is happening in many countries where Barrick Gold is working, discussions in Canada usually take place through the exchange of ideas and not at the same time.
It was therefore sufficient for the mine to open its books, its files and establish a real debate through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust the public opinion and rejects petition and letter of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the views of the same public?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to lawyers who are paid in a way that is not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or you don't want to understand - is that the audience that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does it first because it rejects the brutal way of the mine.
This public is willing to hear and judge Barrick, but on the basis of civilized exchange of arguments, and not as a result of what many perceive as a continuation of the belloon (because of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a stay at the site of the Black Canada authors urging them to stop using this term...).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's continuation is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It rejects, in block, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis for intellectual work.
If it is not possible to study and discuss topics that move the world's rich businesses into a country like Canada, without repeated prosecutions, who will do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by the Black Canada authors.
She has a right to reproduce.
The university environment, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's unmistakable continuation clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she does not want a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abuse.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, have finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic recovery plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has been draining Wall Street for months is still to be buried by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, and a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of the securitised companies.
The US Secretary of Treasury, Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to open up the real economy and ordinary Americans of the ongoing Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do so, traumaism, chaos and disturbances on the daily life of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours in fear of the effect that would lead to a new failure on investors' mood.
The time limit that had been granted was the opening of the markets this morning.
In late negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election proved rather favourable to the agreement, but failed to express their discontent that they were forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has been awarded the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that to allow owners to keep their home and the salary of the heads of companies rescued by the State.
"When taxpayers are asked to take special measures because of the irresponsibleness of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the waves of American television.
Questioned on another line to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The great lines that I have read show that this is something that we are all going to have to digest and with which we are going to be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700-billion-dollar plan aims to purchase, with taxpayers' money, suspicious, risk-weighted and inventable loans from US financial institutions.
It occurs after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (repressed) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (CCAA) and triggering a liquidity freeze and the disbanding of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican electors who had headed the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to be out of this impasse since the Democrats have accepted that some "toxic" assets of the companies in difficulty are provided only by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government had to make losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion, to which 100 billion will be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be entered by another vote of the Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will receive participation in the securitised companies that will benefit him from dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torture is past.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the arrest procedures for housing related to the real estate loan concerned and to set limits on remuneration and off-balance sheet payments to the managers of the affected enterprises.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives from today, and to the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have green light.
Votes continued to rise against this project yesterday, both in the republican and democratic camp.
"Of course, Washington doesn't mean you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, at the address of his electors.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is to benefit taxpayers."
An animator of a small group in Congress named "the caucus of skeptics", the Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, have written to us to say that we are asked not to press and carefully examine the way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion).
The intervention of the Governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas indicated that it had refused to acquire its full-fledged competitor since it lost EUR 2 billion (2.9 billion) in the U.S. in the crisis of real estate loans.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty-largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"It is not of lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, there is a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It's just something that the savers and the households now appreciate that the times are predicting uncertainty."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Manche, the British government seemed to nationalize another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would recover all current loans from Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize from the beginning of this financial crisis.
