Over-the-counter psychology: why do we spend more money?
In the course of sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the commodity.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the Science magazine, human beings do not want to be separated during this type of competition, such as sales to auctions on eBay, and that is why they prefer to pay too high a price.
These research tried to develop a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" with the help of sales to experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was playing the lot, while the other group was involved in a sale to the gaming auctions, while with a functional magnetic resonance process (IRMf), researchers analysed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants were able to earn money, but during the sale of auctions, an essential element of which is the overfill of a third, the whole being under the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise of prices is explained by the escape from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued their analysis of financial surveillance.
In these cases, three groups faced a partner, under different circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the party, then they would receive 15 additional dollars, in reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is that the emphasis was placed on one on victory, while on the other on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the team of players "against failure" were available to higher positions than those performed by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any already existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them did not explain the phenomena found in sales to auctions but by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by now starting on a third explanation." - Andrew Schutter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when do we have to consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that hundreds of miles of hepatitis virus carriers in Hungary, but only seven miles of treatment is followed. This is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly propagated in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g., food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is strongly recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a bad general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then, on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowish, the cells become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Throughout the world, every year a million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or hepatic cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only one patient in ten receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to a cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus because the pathogen destroys the cells of the liver in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing tests.
Pollution is much higher than the average of a population of three groups: people who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients have chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended that you consult your doctor as soon as you experience symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On 30 September, the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004, was organized by the agencies representing the sick of the four corners of the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver caused by viruses, to the causes of its development and to the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
British daily Telegraph has published an article that says that researchers at Oxford University have made an interesting experience to analyze the extent to which belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this experience for the least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude a large part of suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experience takes place in the following way: an instrument that emits sparks and disseminates electrochocs is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look at two paintings sustainably, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady at the hermine painted by Leonardo de Vinci in the 15th century.
Researchers from the origin of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not very different from the first, had a soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an IRM scanner, and during that time received 20 electrochocs in four successive parts, while looking at either the painting on a religious theme or the painting on a more general theme.
The Catholics stated that in the view of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "safe", as if one of them were "careful" and they were "slow, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% of their pain unless they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experience, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in the athetes, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image in which they respond very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, bishop of England, welcomed the results of these research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, effectively change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is no longer any question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if we show believers a Madone painted by Leonard or a painter of the same caliber?
Would the view of a better-quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
