The Smart Car Imitates the Flight of the Bourdon
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle if it was not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, the one with the bees.
In the surprising project presented at the CEATEC, which took place in Japan, Burdonant bees gave the strategic idea of departure to engineers at Nissan to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacles detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot, a bio-inspired auto-robotized system, of type BR23C, which has equipped quality bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flights, each bee is its own space, in oval form, which, in fact, looks much like our safe protective helmet - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the Department of Research and Development and the company's technological public relations.
The bee facet eye plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the face-to-face eye functions, engineers have addressed the idea of laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the ship's microprocessor, which transforms it into an escape route immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system at present, this avoiding manoeuvre takes place in an instinctive manner.
"If not, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protection envelope, a layer where the collision is now considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
In contrast to bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of infinite combinations that have bees to avoid other bees, in our case, we were able to use only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and the concentration of energy is larger, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only treat a few signals coming in a second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-octets of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a giga-octets capacity, or even of mega-octets.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology used for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter the serial cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its integration into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his path.
