Industrial prices continued to increase
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to the month of August 2007 - reported by the Central Statistics Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to those of a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry were only increased by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first production of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials have resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
This was the result of a deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase of 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent an important weight in the national industrial operation, prices have increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the internal sales of processing sectors, these are the prices of the oil processing sector that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical products industry, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverages and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the production of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent during the past year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of those of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, these are the investment profit-initiators that have shown the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the production of consumer goods, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials producing sectors for subsequent processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase was observed in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the production sectors of consumer goods, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors it was reduced by 1.4 per cent.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
