Járóka said: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, whose host is France, has begun in Paris as a representative of the current Presidency of the European Union.
In his message to the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons of the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party Fidesz, drew attention to segregations in education, because it is a violation of the right that affects the most Roma children and therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of legal protection and European civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the group of MP Fidesz Popular Party, Járóka warned that, in addition to the distinctions found in employment, Roma disappear from the labour market, first, following their low qualifications.
"A overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have secondary diplomas, and as a result of an elementary education of poor quality, only a small part has the opportunity to obtain a higher degree of education."
Járóka also stressed that education as a fundamental human right plays a key role when it comes to asserting other fundamental rights.
Investment in early education of Roma children means strengthening the economy of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the honourable Member, there is a need to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, including between Roma and non-Romas.
Indeed, sooner a Roma child starts school, the more he increases his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from his income and consumption, he participates in the State budget.
"Because of their nationality in the European Union, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education, and protected from low quality and sectoral education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the honourable Member, cooperation from the European Union towards a goal and action is necessary for the immediate acceleration of the school disengagement process, and for this reason compliance with existing and preparatory anti-discrimination directives is of primary importance.
"It is necessary to break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment; it is necessary to give the opportunities provided by democracy to Roma children, so that they can participate as citizens of the right to the future of Europe" - Járóka demanded.
On behalf of the European Year for Equal Opportunities, which is ensured for all, the objective of the European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which has been organised each year since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a unique platform to support measures taken to promote equal opportunities and to combat discrimination at European and Member State level.
