The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: these past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that paid the costs mainly: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is headed with 82 single rooms lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the event of the multiplex, as these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-story cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilie-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observed Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a room is closed in a city, these participants are not all necessarily willing to go to multiplex.
